<username>Merek Chang< /username><time>1463810761664</time><Rate>4<//Rate><Text>About once or twice a year I find myself at puente hills mall, whether it's for an after dinner stroll with family or just for nostalgia, I am always warmed in the heart to see that Champs is still around. How is this possible? I have no clue.

Champs is basically the discount version of foot locker, hawking both footwear and t shirts and sportswear at low prices. If I am ever in need of a cheap t-shirt this is where I would go to. They often have interesting stuff that you won't find elsewhere. They specialize is selling sportswear that is outdated but not retro yet. (Like wearing a LeBron James Miami Heat t-shirt in 2016).

If I ever come to the mall I must stop here, to relive my middle school days of coming to this spot and just to see what new (er....old ) inventory they have on hand.< /Text>< pics>

My experience is that it seems like an honest and reputable shop. Their labor cost is 148 per hour, but they undercharged me for time spent, so it was in effect lower than that. They would only put in a manufacturer-made alternator, explaining they want to trust the part. It was about 300 more expensive than a Duralast part from AutoZone, but that's fair and reasonable, and they were transparent about it. Frank and my mechanic who was talking about his old GTI were both friendly and happy to share lots of info. They stuck with their estimate though they let me know it took some hours extra. Positive experience and good shop. They did the promised work at the price I agreed to, and I definitely get the impression they're running an honest shop. 5 stars deserved.

<user_name>Tracy Berry< /user_name>< time>

<rating>2< /rating>< Review>
This was going to be a 5-star review. The food was excellent - we had brussels sprouts as a starter and shared a burger with duck bacon as the main. The server was a bit "green" - he just poured our wine after opening it without having us taste it first - but he was attentive. The problem came when we settled the bill. The menu had showcased 30% off a bottle of wine with entree purchase. The discount was not applied on the bill. When we asked about it, the manager came out and told us he could not take the discount off the wine because there was no way to do it in their computer system. <Rating>5< /Rating><text>Delage is so good it's almost infuriating. How can the food be so good at such a low price point (for omakase at this level, anyway; $65 is still a decent amount to throw down for one meal)?! I'm still not sure, but go for the stellar sushi and the fun, more Western-leaning elements of your course meal. When I went I was pleasantly surprised by some of the nigiri I've never had before (blueback sprat and barracuda, for instance). The least successful dish in my mind was the pork tenderloin (though in general I'm not a huge fan of lean pork), but even that dish had an interesting pairing of a mushroom sauce and a cranberry-apple puree.

I do wish Delage wouldn't serve the seriously overfished bluefin, though. But damn was that chutoro good.<//text><pics>None< /pics>< Response>

<user>103697346167585249774< /user><user_name>Simon Lau<//user_name><time>1615173982638<//time>< rate>

< text>
My first visit here two weeks ago was good.  Ordered a sampling of five different tacos for the family served on plates.  The staff was really attentive with two windows open and each pair serving food ans handling transactions.  The tacos were good although the sauce had begun to soak through the tacos by the time I was working through them making it into a delightful mess.  My second visit here unfortunately wasn't that great.  One window was opened serving food while the second window handled the payment in cash.  The tacos were wrapped in foil and by the time I got home, the corn tortillas had started to break apart making it very difficult to enjoy.  With a large orders of 21 tacos, I was expecting a better meal with the family.  I found the meats to be much drier on this visit and the quality of the meats not so good.  So maybe I'll have to give this some more thought on my next street tacos cravings.<//text>

<username>Lisa Wu<//username><Review>Was traveling on business and passing through Pasadena on Valentine's Day. After a long day of business meetings I was finally able to reunite with my boyfriend right after midnight. We started looking for places that are still open for dinner and the Los California Tacos truck was pretty much the only place that still offers food after midnight within a one mile radius so we decided to give it a shot. < Review>
Lovely local taco truck. Definitely walking distance to where I live but I always drive and there is only ever a line or tough parking around 7 on a weekend night. Try the meats and you won't be disappointed. I am a big fan of their Al Pastor and Carnitas, but you can't go wrong with any one. I will say in honesty that I once did get lengua which was a little dry/ overcooked but every other time I've ordered it, it had been some of the best tongue in town.
Also: try the horchata or the all fresca drinks. Definitely both are very sweet but both are good, seems to be made in a blender beforehand and not in one of those big churning machines but idk for sure.< /Review>
